Hidden-state h(t) dynamics followed


τh(t)=−h(t)+f[Wrech(t)+Winx(t)+brec]+η(t)f(x)=max(x,0)y(t)=Wouth(t)+bout
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{gathered}\tau \boldsymbol{h}(t)=-\boldsymbol{h}(t)+f\left[\boldsymbol{W}_{\text {rec }} \boldsymbol{h}(t)+\boldsymbol{W}_{\text {in }} x(t)+\boldsymbol{b}_{\text {rec }}\right]+\boldsymbol{\eta}(t) \\ f(x)=\max (x, 0) \\ \boldsymbol{y}(t)=W_{\text {out }} \boldsymbol{h}(t)+b_{\text {out }}\end{gathered}$$\end{document}

A cross was defined as the first time point t∗ at which the network output y(t∗) ≥ 0.5. The desired output trajectory y∽(t) was specified as a step function transitioning at the target escape


y~(t)={0,t<ttar,1,t≥ttar.
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \tilde{y}(t)= \begin{cases}0, & t<t_{t a r}, \\ 1, & t \geq t_{t a r} .\end{cases}$$\end{document}



time ttar, which combines the door-opening time and the experimentally measured behavioral latency measured in rats (latency for CS present: 48.7s, latency for CS absent: 111.3s):


ttar={tdoor+ℓCS=90+d+48.7s,CS present,tdoor+ℓnoCS=90+d+111.3s,CS absent,
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle t_{\mathrm{tar}}= \begin{cases}t_{\mathrm{door}}+\ell_{\mathrm{CS}}=90+d+48.7 \mathrm{~s}, & \text { CS present }, \\ t_{\mathrm{door}}+\ell_{\mathrm{noCS}}=90+d+111.3 \mathrm{~s}, & \text { CS absent },\end{cases}$$\end{document}

The per-trial loss function minimized during training was:


L=−∑t[y~ln⁡y+(1−y~)ln⁡(1−y)]+λ(‖Win‖+‖Wrec‖)+λFR⟨‖h(t)‖22⟩t
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \mathcal{L}=-\sum_{t}[\tilde{y} \ln y+(1-\tilde{y}) \ln (1-y)]+\lambda\left(\left\|\mathbf{W}_{\mathrm{in}}\right\|+\left\|\mathbf{W}_{\text {rec }}\right\|\right)+\lambda_{F R}\left\langle\|\mathrm{~h}(\mathrm{t})\|_{2}^{2}\right\rangle_{t}$$\end{document}

For each discrete state j of Y and each combination of states k from a source A (either X₁ alone, X₂ alone, or their joint distribution [X₁, X₂]), we computed the corresponding conditional probabilities required for PID analysis.


P(A=k∣Y=j)=P(Y=j,A=k)/P(Y=j),P(Y=j∣A=k)=P(Y=j,A=k)/P(A=k)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle P(A=k \mid Y=j)=P(Y=j, A=k) / P(Y=j), P(Y=j \mid A=k)=P(Y=j, A=k) / P(A=k)$$\end{document}

The information that source A conveys about Y when Y is in state j is then


I(Y=j;A)=∑kP(Y=j,A=k)log2⁡P(Y=j∣A=k)P(Y=j)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle I(Y=j ; A)=\sum_{k} P(Y=j, A=k) \log _{2} \frac{P(Y=j \mid A=k)}{P(Y=j)}$$\end{document}
